<h4 class="news-story-title"><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://daily.bandcamp.com/album-of-the-day/dorcha-honey-badger-review">Dorcha, “Honey Badger”</a></h4><div class="news-story-body col-xs-12">                                                                <div class="mr-byline">     By <a href="/patrick-lyons" target="_blank">Patrick Lyons</a> </div>                                                                                                                        <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://daily.bandcamp.com/album-of-the-day/dorcha-honey-badger-review">daily.bandcamp.com</a>                         &mdash;                                          ALBUM OF THE DAY       Dorcha, “Honey Badger”     By  Patrick Lyons · November 16, 2020     ​ ​                               ...    Honey Badger Dorcha   .         /      pre-order buy    pre-order buy    you own this         wishlist         in wishlist        go to album go to track   go to album go to track              .   00:10 / 00:58           Birmingham, UK group Dorcha take their name from a Scottish Gaelic word with multiple meanings: dark, dusky, enigmatic.                                           </div><h4 class="news-story-title"><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.stereogum.com/2031231/lords-of-chaos-jonas-akerlund-review/franchises/columns/sounding-board/">&#x27;Lords Of Chaos&#x27;: The Black Metal Movie Is A Bloody Mess</a></h4><div class="news-story-body col-xs-12">                                                                <div class="mr-byline">     By <a href="/patrick-lyons" target="_blank">Patrick Lyons</a> </div>                                                                                                                        <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.stereogum.com/2031231/lords-of-chaos-jonas-akerlund-review/franchises/columns/sounding-board/">stereogum.com</a>                         &mdash;                                          Even if you’ve never heard a note of Mayhem’s music or don’t listen to black metal, the abrasive subgenre they’re credited with creating, you probably know bits and pieces of the Norwegian band’s brief-but-newsworthy history. They burnt churches. One member killed himself. A second member murdered a third. That second member has since become a lightning rod for modern-day white nationalism and Nazism.                                           </div><h4 class="news-story-title"><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.stereogum.com/2020358/refused-shape-of-punk-to-come-turns-20/franchises/reviews/the-anniversary/">Was Refused&#x27;s &#x27;The Shape Of Punk To Come&#x27; Actually The Shape Of Punk To Come?</a></h4><div class="news-story-body col-xs-12">                                                                <div class="mr-byline">     By <a href="/patrick-lyons" target="_blank">Patrick Lyons</a> </div>                                                                                                                        <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.stereogum.com/2020358/refused-shape-of-punk-to-come-turns-20/franchises/reviews/the-anniversary/">stereogum.com</a>                         &mdash;                                          “They told me that the classics never go out of style, but… they do, they do. Somehow, baby? I never thought that we do too.”Those are the first words spoken on Refused’s The Shape Of Punk To Come — which came out 20 years ago this Saturday, on October 27, 1998. Not even 30 seconds in, the album’s already obsessed with its own historical significance: There’s the brash prediction of the title, and the fatalism of the opening line.                                           </div><h4 class="news-story-title"><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.stereogum.com/2101021/waka-flocka-flame-flockaveli-turns-10/franchises/reviews/the-anniversary/">Waka Flocka Flame&#x27;s &#x27;Flockaveli&#x27; Came Out 10 Years Ago Today</a></h4><div class="news-story-body col-xs-12">                                                                <div class="mr-byline">     By <a href="/patrick-lyons" target="_blank">Patrick Lyons</a> </div>                                                                                                                        <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.stereogum.com/2101021/waka-flocka-flame-flockaveli-turns-10/franchises/reviews/the-anniversary/">stereogum.com</a>                         &mdash;                                          It’s a crudely animated video in the tradition of eBaum’s World hits like “End Of Ze World” and “Sensimilla Street,” which range from cheekily irreverent to so offensive Matt Stone and Trey Parker would blush. Likenesses of Southern rappers Soulja Boy, OJ Da Juiceman, Gucci Mane, and Waka Flocka Flame deliver self-deprecating verses that highlight their respective shortcomings as rappers, from Soulja’s mindlessly repetitive hook to Gucci’s slurry Boomhauer-isms.                                           </div><h4 class="news-story-title"><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.stereogum.com/1971652/the-lonesome-crowded-west-turns-20/franchises/reviews/the-anniversary/">Modest Mouse&#x27;s Great American Album is 20, but it hits harder now than ever.</a></h4><div class="news-story-body col-xs-12">                                                                <div class="mr-byline">     By <a href="/patrick-lyons" target="_blank">Patrick Lyons</a> </div>                                                                                                                        <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.stereogum.com/1971652/the-lonesome-crowded-west-turns-20/franchises/reviews/the-anniversary/">stereogum.com</a>                         &mdash;                                          When Modest Mouse released their second album — on November 18, 1997; 20 years ago this Saturday — the Seattle area was in a state of flux.                                           </div><h4 class="news-story-title"><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.stereogum.com/2098556/microphones-it-was-hot-we-stayed-in-the-water/franchises/reviews/the-anniversary/">The Microphones&#x27; &#x27;It Was Hot, We Stayed In The Water&#x27; Was Phil Elverum&#x27;s First Masterpiece</a></h4><div class="news-story-body col-xs-12">                                                                <div class="mr-byline">     By <a href="/patrick-lyons" target="_blank">Patrick Lyons</a> </div>                                                                                                                        <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.stereogum.com/2098556/microphones-it-was-hot-we-stayed-in-the-water/franchises/reviews/the-anniversary/">stereogum.com</a>                         &mdash;                                          “It starts with a beautifully recorded chord on acoustic guitar for a while before the singing starts. And I really liked how it goes on for long enough that it ushers you into a new place. You forget the world you were in before you started listening to the album.”That’s Phil Elverum in a recent NPR interview, describing the opening moments of a song from Red House Painters’ 1996 album Songs For A Blue Guitar by way of also describing the opening moments of two of his own albums.                                           </div><h4 class="news-story-title"><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/dave-b-rain-new-song.1963936.html">Dave B - Rain</a></h4><div class="news-story-body col-xs-12">                                                                <div class="mr-byline">     By <a href="/patrick-lyons" target="_blank">Patrick Lyons</a> </div>                                                                                                                        <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/dave-b-rain-new-song.1963936.html">hotnewhiphop.com</a>                         &mdash;                                          RainEditor Rating:HOTTTTTUser Rating:Dave B drops &quot;Rain.&quot;Back in January, we introduced you to Seattle spitter Dave B with a pair of dope tracks called &quot;Leaves&quot; and &quot;Do That,&quot; and now he&#x27;s back with another. This one&#x27;s called &quot;Rain,&quot; and the production on it (handled by Stewart Villain) is a little more adventurous this time around. Whereas its predecessors rolled along with easygoing boom-bap vibes, this one&#x27;s somehow both more earthy and more synthetic.                                           </div><h4 class="news-story-title"><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/dave-b-leaves-prod-by-jake-one-new-song.1962010.html">Dave B - Leaves  (Prod. By Jake One)</a></h4><div class="news-story-body col-xs-12">                                                                <div class="mr-byline">     By <a href="/patrick-lyons" target="_blank">Patrick Lyons</a> </div>                                                                                                                        <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/dave-b-leaves-prod-by-jake-one-new-song.1962010.html">hotnewhiphop.com</a>                         &mdash;                                          Leaves Editor Rating:HOTTTTTUser Rating:Seattle&#x27;s Dave B makes his HNHH debut with &quot;Leaves.&quot;Although Seattle isn&#x27;t commonly thought of as a hub for hip-hop, it&#x27;s got a pretty great scene of its own, with lots of underground artists making noise in the Northwest. You&#x27;ve got guys like Ugly Frank and Nacho Picasso who make dark, foreboding jams, Shabazz Palaces making futuristic space funk, and producers like Jake One and Blue Sky Black Death soundtracking all of it.                                           </div><h4 class="news-story-title"><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.spin.com/2020/05/feel-the-wrath-of-the-fuckin-devilation-three-6-mafias-mystic-stylez-turns-25/">Feel the Wrath of the Fuckin’ Devilation: Three 6 Mafia’s &#x27;Mystic Stylez&#x27; Turns 25</a></h4><div class="news-story-body col-xs-12">                                                                <div class="mr-byline">     By <a href="/patrick-lyons" target="_blank">Patrick Lyons</a> </div>                                                                                                                        <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.spin.com/2020/05/feel-the-wrath-of-the-fuckin-devilation-three-6-mafias-mystic-stylez-turns-25/">spin.com</a>                         &mdash;                                          Mystic Styles of the ancient mutilationsTorture chambers filled with corpses in my basementFeel the wrath of the fuckin’ devilationThree 6 Mafia: creation of SatanBy the time Lord Infamous uttered that incantation, it had been seven years since the FBI threatened N.W.A. over “Fuck Tha Police,” four since Scarface had “visions of bodies being burned,” two since Method Man and Raekwon recorded a skit about vivisecting victims with red-hot hangers and rusty screwdrivers.                                           </div><h4 class="news-story-title"><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/classic-rotation-futures-pluto-news.31222.html">Classic Rotation: Future&#x27;s &quot;Pluto&quot;</a></h4><div class="news-story-body col-xs-12">                                                                <div class="mr-byline">     By <a href="/patrick-lyons" target="_blank">Patrick Lyons</a> </div>                                                                                                                        <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/classic-rotation-futures-pluto-news.31222.html">hotnewhiphop.com</a>                         &mdash;                                          Five years ago, Future emerged with an album that initially confused the masses but was quickly absorbed into the fabric of rap music.  Take a moment, if you will, to revisit to Future&#x27;s debut album, Pluto, which crash-landed on this planet exactly five years ago. When compared to the rest of rap music in 2017, does anything about this album seem particularly weird or groundbreaking?                                           </div><h4 class="news-story-title"><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.gq.com/story/young-dolph-interview-2020">Why Memphis Rapper Young Dolph Photoshopped Face Masks on His Old Album Covers</a></h4><div class="news-story-body col-xs-12">                                                                <div class="mr-byline">     By <a href="/patrick-lyons" target="_blank">Patrick Lyons</a> </div>                                                                                                                        <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.gq.com/story/young-dolph-interview-2020">gq.com</a>                         &mdash;                                          A few weeks ago, the Memphis rapper Young Dolph announced his new single, “Sunshine,” by posting its lurid artwork on Instagram. Cartoonishly depicting a glaring Donald Trump, a bleeding American flag, a couple of military-grade Hummers, and at the center of it all, a masked doctor holding a ventilator to a patient’s mouth, it’s the most aggressive and blatantly extra visual reference to coronavirus we’ve seen in music thus far.                                           </div><h4 class="news-story-title"><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.stereogum.com/2082555/dynamite-hack-boyz-in-the-hood-acoustic-rap-covers/franchises/sounding-board/">Dynamite Hack&#x27;s &quot;Boyz In The Hood&quot; Paved The Way For 20 Years Of Awful Acoustic Rap Covers</a></h4><div class="news-story-body col-xs-12">                                                                <div class="mr-byline">     By <a href="/setlistfms-count" target="_blank">Setlist.fm’s count</a>, <a href="/patrick-lyons" target="_blank">Patrick Lyons</a> </div>                                                                                                                        <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.stereogum.com/2082555/dynamite-hack-boyz-in-the-hood-acoustic-rap-covers/franchises/sounding-board/">stereogum.com</a>                         &mdash;                                          “Some people tell me I’m a genius… that I’m forcing white America to listen to the problems of black America, that I’m tricking them into listening to the song by putting it to this sweet music. Honestly, I really didn’t think about it that much.”That’s Dynamite Hack frontman Mark Morris, discussing his band’s cover of Eazy-E’s “Boyz-N-The-Hood,” released 20 years ago this month.                                           </div><h4 class="news-story-title"><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.gq.com/gallery/anton-tammi-the-weeknd-after-hours-interview-2020">How One Director Helped Shape The Weeknd’s &#x27;After Hours&#x27; Aesthetic</a></h4><div class="news-story-body col-xs-12">                                                                <div class="mr-byline">     By <a href="/patrick-lyons" target="_blank">Patrick Lyons</a> </div>                                                                                                                        <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.gq.com/gallery/anton-tammi-the-weeknd-after-hours-interview-2020">gq.com</a>                         &mdash;                                          The music video for “Heartless,” the lead single from The Weeknd’s new album, After Hours, opens with Abel Tesfaye standing in the port-cochère of a Las Vegas casino. He turns his gaze upward and grins ear-to-ear as overhead lights dance on his sunglasses. The “In Your Eyes” video, his most recent, closes with actress Zaina Miuccia holding Tesfaye’s decapitated head—still wearing those shades—aloft against a dramatic sunset.                                           </div><h4 class="news-story-title"><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/rgpe5j/shoes-10-years-later-interview">Ten Years of &quot;Shoes,&quot; the Story of the First Great Viral Music Video, Betch</a></h4><div class="news-story-body col-xs-12">                                                                <div class="mr-byline">     By <a href="/patrick-lyons" target="_blank">Patrick Lyons</a> </div>                                                                                                                        <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/rgpe5j/shoes-10-years-later-interview">vice.com</a>                         &mdash;                                          “Shoes.”thump thump thump“Shoes.”thump thump thump&quot;Shoes.&quot;thump thump thump“Oh my god... Shoes.”You remember. It was delivered in a flat monotone, the rallying cry of Kelly, a teenage girl whose parents and brother simply don’t understand her unending drive for footwear. Strutting between boutiques, she’s the Pontius Pilate of platforms and pumps: “These shoes rule,” she proclaims.                                           </div><h4 class="news-story-title"><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/9344603/artists-who-worked-remotely-coronavirus">10 Artists Who Pioneered Working Remotely</a></h4><div class="news-story-body col-xs-12">                                                                <div class="mr-byline">     By <a href="/patrick-lyons" target="_blank">Patrick Lyons</a> </div>                                                                                                                        <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/9344603/artists-who-worked-remotely-coronavirus">billboard.com</a>                         &mdash;                                          With the entire world currently facing some form of self-isolation, it’s inevitable that the steady IV drip of music that we usually receive will begin to slow. Bands can’t get together to write and rehearse; professional studios’ doors are closed; music videos, merch, and other promotional items will be difficult to come by. We’ve already seen musicians adapting to a world devoid of concerts and gigs by ramping up their livestreaming games, but what about the production of new, original music?                                           </div><h4 class="news-story-title"><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://daily.bandcamp.com/lists/a-brief-guide-to-nicolas-jaars-wildly-inventive-electronic-music">A Brief Guide to Nicolas Jaar’s Wildly Inventive Electronic Music</a></h4><div class="news-story-body col-xs-12">                                                                <div class="mr-byline">     By <a href="/patrick-lyons" target="_blank">Patrick Lyons</a> </div>                                                                                                                        <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://daily.bandcamp.com/lists/a-brief-guide-to-nicolas-jaars-wildly-inventive-electronic-music">daily.bandcamp.com</a>                         &mdash;                                          LISTS   A Brief Guide to Nicolas Jaar’s Wildly Inventive Electronic Music    By  Patrick Lyons · March 20, 2020             In a 2009 interview, a then-19-year-old Nicolas Jaar listed the minimalist composer Erik Satie and Ethiopian jazz musician Mulatu Astatke as his primary influences—heady stuff for an electronic music “it” kid.                                           </div><h4 class="news-story-title"><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.stereogum.com/2074026/caribou-suddenly-interview/franchises/interview/">Caribou &#x27;Suddenly&#x27; Interview</a></h4><div class="news-story-body col-xs-12">                                                                <div class="mr-byline">     By <a href="/patrick-lyons" target="_blank">Patrick Lyons</a> </div>                                                                                                                        <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.stereogum.com/2074026/caribou-suddenly-interview/franchises/interview/">stereogum.com</a>                         &mdash;                                          If there’s one moment on Caribou’s upcoming album Suddenly that boils down its elastic essence, it’s the transition from verse to chorus on second single “You And I.” Initially, the song floats on pillowy chords, a twinkling lead melody, and a persistent midtempo beat, instantly recalling the spaciest moments on the last Caribou album, 2015’s Our Love.                                           </div><h4 class="news-story-title"><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8551236/matthew-wilder-break-my-stride-interview-tik-tok">The TikTok Revival of Matthew Wilder&#x27;s 1983 Hit &#x27;Break My Stride&#x27; Is Just the Latest Turn in His Unpredictable Career</a></h4><div class="news-story-body col-xs-12">                                                                <div class="mr-byline">     By <a href="/patrick-lyons" target="_blank">Patrick Lyons</a> </div>                                                                                                                        <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8551236/matthew-wilder-break-my-stride-interview-tik-tok">billboard.com</a>                         &mdash;                                          By now, anyone with so much as a pinky on the pulse of popular music knows that TikTok is a force to be reckoned with when it comes to breaking new music. Most notably, the video-sharing platform was credited with boosting Lil Nas X’s “Old Town Road” into the Hot 100, where it soon began a record-breaking run of dominance.                                           </div><h4 class="news-story-title"><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8551033/tame-impala-slow-rush-soft-rock-influences">The Soft Rock Backbone of Tame Impala&#x27;s &#x27;The Slow Rush&#x27;: 10 Key Influences</a></h4><div class="news-story-body col-xs-12">                                                                <div class="mr-byline">     By <a href="/patrick-lyons" target="_blank">Patrick Lyons</a> </div>                                                                                                                        <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8551033/tame-impala-slow-rush-soft-rock-influences">billboard.com</a>                         &mdash;                                          In typical press release form, the press release for Tame Impala’s upcoming album, The Slow Rush, makes some lofty claims. “Continuing the expansion of a musical palette that started at psych rock and shattered from [debut album] Innerspeaker upwards, The Slow Rush explores new space and sounds,” it gushes.                                           </div><h4 class="news-story-title"><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.gq.com/story/lil-wayne-funeral-type-beat">When Your Seven-Year-Old Beat Winds Up on a Lil Wayne Album</a></h4><div class="news-story-body col-xs-12">                                                                <div class="mr-byline">     By <a href="/patrick-lyons" target="_blank">Patrick Lyons</a> </div>                                                                                                                        <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.gq.com/story/lil-wayne-funeral-type-beat">gq.com</a>                         &mdash;                                          When Lil Wayne’s last album, Tha Carter V, came out, it was no surprise that its tracks were culled from a wide variety of sessions, producers, and even eras. Originally planned for a 2014 release, the album didn’t arrive until late 2018 due to a dispute between Wayne and his longtime label, Cash Money Records.                                           </div><h4 class="news-story-title"><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://uproxx.com/music/five-types-album-of-the-year-grammys/">Five Album Types That Get Nominated For The Album Of The Year Grammy</a></h4><div class="news-story-body col-xs-12">                                                                <div class="mr-byline">     By <a href="/patrick-lyons" target="_blank">Patrick Lyons</a> </div>                                                                                                                        <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://uproxx.com/music/five-types-album-of-the-year-grammys/">uproxx.com</a>                         &mdash;                                          The Grammys can be a little insular and predictable. That’s not exactly a hot take. But of all the various awards and categories, nothing’s as formulaic as the nominations for the biggest award of them all, Album Of The Year. Of the past four AOTY winners, three had been nominated for the award in previous years. The fourth, Kacey Musgraves, had previously been nominated for five Grammys in different categories, winning two.                                           </div><h4 class="news-story-title"><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.stereogum.com/2070605/dan-bejar-interview-destroyer-have-we-met/franchises/interview/">Destroyer &#x27;Have We Met&#x27; Interview: Dan Bejar On His Attempt At &quot;Computer Music&quot;</a></h4><div class="news-story-body col-xs-12">                                                                <div class="mr-byline">     By <a href="/patrick-lyons" target="_blank">Patrick Lyons</a> </div>                                                                                                                        <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.stereogum.com/2070605/dan-bejar-interview-destroyer-have-we-met/franchises/interview/">stereogum.com</a>                         &mdash;                                          It’s been said before, quite possibly about every album Destroyer’s released in the past 15 years, but the latest, Have We Met, is a very different Destroyer album. On one hand, it’s dark, eerie, and volatile. Ghostly wisps of synths glide past lyrics dripping with dread. Craggy guitar lines emerge out of nothingness and then all of the sudden, tower over everything.                                           </div><h4 class="news-story-title"><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://uproxx.com/music/best-new-artist-grammys-history/">The Least-New Best New Artist Winners In Grammy History</a></h4><div class="news-story-body col-xs-12">                                                                <div class="mr-byline">     By <a href="/patrick-lyons" target="_blank">Patrick Lyons</a> </div>                                                                                                                        <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://uproxx.com/music/best-new-artist-grammys-history/">uproxx.com</a>                         &mdash;                                          In 2019, Lizzo scored two Top 5 hits on the Billboard Hot 100 via songs that were released in 2016 and 2017. This is rare, but not forbidden — nothing in Billboard’s chart eligibility rules bars older material. In fact, just under two months after Lizzo’s 2017 track “Truth Hurts” fell from its No. 1 position, Mariah Carey’s 1994 single “All I Want for Christmas is You” hit the top of the chart.                                           </div><h4 class="news-story-title"><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8547834/neil-peart-rush-freedom-of-music-eulogy">Neil Peart: Rush Drummer/Lyricist Believed in the Freedom of Music</a></h4><div class="news-story-body col-xs-12">                                                                <div class="mr-byline">     By <a href="/patrick-lyons" target="_blank">Patrick Lyons</a> </div>                                                                                                                        <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8547834/neil-peart-rush-freedom-of-music-eulogy">billboard.com</a>                         &mdash;                                          Neil Peart was an extraordinary being sent to Earth to destroy drummer jokes. Drummer jokes, if you’re not familiar, are a subcategory of music nerd humor that lampoon the least melodic, least theory-driven member of most bands (bassist jokes also exist, for what it’s worth). For example: What do you call someone who hangs around musicians? A drummer. Or: What do you call a drummer with half a brain? Gifted.                                           </div><h4 class="news-story-title"><a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://medium.com/@patlyons91/decade-chasers-pt-2-41bdb858a80a">Decade Chasers, Pt. 2</a></h4><div class="news-story-body col-xs-12">                                                                <div class="mr-byline">     By <a href="/patrick-lyons" target="_blank">Patrick Lyons</a> </div>                                                                                                                        <a target="_blank" rel="noreferrer" href="https://medium.com/@patlyons91/decade-chasers-pt-2-41bdb858a80a">medium.com</a>                         &mdash;                                          DeafheavenConfession: 10 years ago, I didn’t listen to metal. That’s at odds with my taste now, the music I play now, and how I present myself now. But hey, life’s about growing and changing, isn’t it? In high school and prior, I wasn’t friends with many metal fans, and that made a huge difference. Similarly to emo (which is an entirely different essay), metal was somewhat of a maligned genre among my peers, especially among the people I looked up to.                                           </div>